range: Widespread across north and eastern Australia.
description: Perennial shrub with rough leaves and trailing stems. The flowers are large, disc-shaped and bright watermelon pink in colour.
cultivation: Plant in a well-drained area with full or partial sun and allow plants to dry out when foliage dies off in the dry season.

range: Fairly common along the east coast rainforests .
description: Medium shrub growing to 8m with herbaceous branchlets. Leaves are large up to 20cm and ovate in shape with toothed margins. Panicles of white flowers are followed by clusters of purple berries.
cultivation: Over time this plant forms a bushy shrub that can make a useful plant for a garden midstorey. Plant in a semi-shaded, moister position. Often becomes leggy but this can easily be rectified with annual pruning.

range: Locally common in eastern Australia in dry habitats.
description: Small shrub to 1.5m high with slightly hairy stems and phyllodes. Phyllodes are ovate in shape with prominent midvein and sharp point. Flowers are born from phyllode axils in solitary globose heads with 12-18 bright yellow flowers. Seed pods strongly curved with seeds constricted.
cultivation: Grows well in sunny spots with ordinary, drier soils that have a sandy base and roughly neutral pH. Grows well as an informal hedge or as a barrier with its spiny leaves keeping out intruders. The prostrate form 'Winter Gold' makes good groundcover and the seeds are popular with birds.

range: Largely restricted to primary subtropical rainforest around Brisbane and the Gold Coast.
description: Spreading tree that can grow very tall from 5m to 40m. Bark is finely fissured and greyish-brown in colour. Phyllodes are elliptic and slightly curved to 10cm long with 3 to 4 longitudinal veins. Flowers are in inflorescences of white-cream globular heads. Pods are straight or curved containing numerous round, brown seeds.
cultivation: Grow in a moist, semi-shady spot out of the wind. The plant can grow quite quickly into a large tree so it must have ample room to spread, e.g. 10m. Keep watered in dry spells.

range: South east Queensland to west of Rockhampton. Often grows as an understorey species in Lemon-scented Gum forest.
description: Medium sized shrub that responds well to pruning, yielding wide green phyllodes and many tiny yellow pom pom flower heads often several times per year. Resistant to borers that often create problems in other Acacia species.
cultivation: Grow in a sunny well drained location. Ideal as a screen plant and tolerates coastal conditions with some shelter.

range: Common native to the coastal belt of south east Queensland and northern New South Wales.  Grows in dry sclerophyll forest and in open woodland or scrub on sandstone-based soils and shales.
description: Medium spreading shrub or small tree to 8m. Branches with rough bark. Flower heads between 5 and 10cm long, cylindrical and pale yellow. Seed pods twisted and thick becoming flattened with age.
cultivation: Fast growing shrub or small tree depending on pruning strategy. Evergreen foliage, with winter flowering. Tolerates drier conditions.

range: Widespread along coastal eastern Australia. Natural habitat in coastal heath and swamp.
description: Medium spreading shrub from 0.5 to 4m high. Long narrow phyllodes. Round pom pom golden flowers in winter to spring.
cultivation: Grows in well drained sandy soils. Tolerates full sun and sporadic dry spells.

range: Widespread along coastal eastern Australia.
description: Small tree to 5m high. Clusters of yellow pom pom flowers in autumn to winter.
cultivation: Grows in a range of soil conditions with some drainage. Enjoys full sun.

range: Extends from near Boonah to near Rockhampton. Grows in open Eucalyptus forest on ridges or along creeks
description: Medium tree to 10m with a dense canopy of elliptical green phyllodes. Cream globular flowers from summer to winter.
cultivation: Grows in a range of soil conditions under full sun and useful as a screen of shade tree. Longer living than most Acacias.

range: Grows commonly along the coastal districts of northern New South Wales and sub-tropical Queensland.
description: Spreading shrub or small tree reaching 6m. Tiny globular yellow flower heads. Found in stony, sandy soils in eucalypt woodlands and scrub.
cultivation: Acacia fimbriata is a fast growing shrub or small tree. Grow in well-drained soil in full to part sun. Tolerates light frost.

range: Grows chiefly in heath amongst granite outcrops in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland. Grows mostly in shallow sandy soil over granite at higher elevations, also on sandstone near the coast, in open eucalypt forests, occasionally in heaths or along creeks.
description: Multi-stemmed, flat-topped, shrub to 3 m high. Long narrow phyllodes and pale yellow flower heads.
cultivation: Prefers sandy well drained soil. Grow in a sunny position.

range: Inland specialist from darling downs to mulga lands in central Queensland.
description: Erect or spreading tree usually 5–20 m high; suckers extensively, particularly following disturbance. Forms extensive open-forest communities usually on fertile clay and loamy clay.
cultivation: Grows in clay loam soils in full sun. Extremely drought tolerant. Important species in its native range due to extensive historical clearing.

range: Occurs through most coastal areas of New South Wales and the southern half of Queensland.
description: A shrub or small tree to 8m. Fast growing with creamy yellow flower spikes.
cultivation: Grows in a variety of soils as long as it will not be waterlogged for extended periods.

synonyms: Myrtle Wattle, Myrtle-leaved Acacia, Red-stemmed Wattle
range: Widely occurring through coastal eastern Australia from south east Queensland down to New South Wales and Victoria.
description: Compact shrub between 0.5m to 3m. Dark green phyllodes and creamy yellow flower heads.
cultivation: Plant in most soil types in full sun to partial shade. Can tolerate light frost.

range: Stronghold in north eastern New South Wales and south eastern Queensland including inland areas.
description: Erect or spreading shrub between 3 - 5m. Elongated phyllodes and clusters of yellow globular flower heads.
cultivation: Grows in a variety of soils, but performs best with some drainage. Some drought tolerance.

range: Relatively restricted range in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland hinterland rainforest.
description: Large tree form wattle with pale yellow flower spikes.
cultivation: Enjoys high rainfall areas in a sunny position. Prefers good drainage.

range: Fairley restricted to south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: A shrub that becomes more tree like with maturity. Silvery foliage makes this a unique garden addition. Sun yellow globular flowers.
cultivation: Avoid planting near extensive natural areas. Very fast growing and adaptable to many climes.

range: Coastal south eastern Australia.
description: A sand dune loving wattle. Low dense sprawling shrub to 2m high. Green phyllodes almost have an oval shape to them, with yellow flower spikes
cultivation: Grows best in sandy soil. Very tolerant of salt air, making it perfect for the coastal zone. Hardy in times of drought.

range: North from the Gosford area in New South Wales and into south east Queensland.
description: Medium to large tree to 15m with interesting corky textured grey bark. Lovely tufted white flower clusters in spring followed by red fruits in summer.
cultivation: Some protection needed in early stages. Likes well drained soil. Ornamental flowers, fruit and leaves.

range: Found in littoral rainforests from Yamba to Cap York
description: Bushy shrub or small tree with orange to red brown growth on top of deep glossy green leaves. Clusters of small white flowers followed by white fruit.
cultivation: Mulch and water regularly until the plant is established, usually around 12 weeks. Prune after flowering to promote dense growth habit and flowering, fertilise with a slow release native fertiliser in spring.

range: Grows in rainforest edges from central New South Wales to south east Queensland.
description: Large tree to 20m with creamy mottled trunk. Small white flowers form in bunches in spring.
cultivation: Tolerates relatively poorer soils. Grow in part shade.

range: Coastal species stretching from far north Queensland to central New South Wales.
description: Small to medium tree up to 10m. Cream flowers followed by orange fruits.
cultivation: Plant in full sun with good drainage, even sandy soils. Great coastal plant for windbreak or screen. Tolerates salt laden winds.

range: Well established from north Queensland south along the coast into northern New South Wales.
description: A large shrub to small tree, with compact growth and striking fruit that range from pink to purple in colouration.
cultivation: A fine garden tree with a bushy rounded shape. It is sensitive to poor soil drainage but copes with dry and cold conditions. Great for water-wise gardens.

range: Stronghold in coastal New South Wales but extending partially into south east Queensland. Subtropical and dry rainforest -found along most scrubby watercourses.
description: Medium shrubby tree with dark green and aromatic leaves. Small white flowers followed by pale yellow fruits.
cultivation: Useful screen. Fairly readily cultivated in a well-drained soil and sunny aspect, and benefits from extra water and fertiliser. It is somewhat frost tender when young.

range: Restricted to south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: An attractive tree to 30m with a spreading crown of relatively large glossy leaves.
cultivation: Best planted in rainforest and wet eucalypt areas. Hardy and fast growing in the right conditions.

range: Restricted to south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Shrubby tree to 15m with glossy green leaves and small white flowers.
cultivation: Slower growing and requires a shady protected position.

range: North from the Gosford area in New South Wales and into south east Queensland.
description: Small tree to 9m high. Leaves aromatic when crushed. White flowers and fruit attract birds and butterflies.
cultivation: Suited for sandy soils in full sun or part shade.

range: Native to coastal Queensland and northern Australia.
description: Clumping fern with fronds to 1.5m tall.
cultivation: Coarse glossy green leaves, native to coastal zones. Can grow in well-watered garden position.

range: Found throughout eastern parts of Queensland and New South Wales.
description: A dense, low heath shrub to 1m with red fruits.
cultivation: Grows in many soil types but prefers moisture. Ideal in part shade.

range: Common from north Queensland to Victoria with isolated patches around eastern South Australia and south west Australia.
description: A lacy leaved clumping fern with slender stems. Grows up to 40cm in height.
cultivation: Enjoys a moist location (does not tolerate drought) with good natural light but not direct sun.

range: Occupies the whole New South Wales coast stretching into south east Queensland and far eastern Victoria.
description: Long-creeping, much-branched, attractive and vigorous fern. Delicate in appearance.
cultivation: Suitable for large tubs filled with acidic soils or in sheltered and shady areas. Requires plenty of water and high humidity but otherwise a low maintenance plant.

range: Native through eastern Australian coastal zones.
description: A hardy fern with fronds growing to 55cm. Young fronds are pink or red.
cultivation: Plant is a shady spot with filtered light and moist soil.

range: Scattered populations in rainforest and wet eucalypt forests along eastern Australia.
description: A large tree to 40m with a straight trunk and dense green foliage.
cultivation: This tree needs a large area for growth. Extremely hardy tree, tolerating full sun to part shade, most soil types and resistant to frost, drought and coastal exposure.

range: Native to the northern parts of south east Queensland stretching all the way north then wrapping around the north east coast of Western Australia.
description: A shrub to small tree of 15m with clusters of fragrant white flowers that develop into bright red fruit.
cultivation: Grows best in a protected position, but is a fairly hardy plant.

range: Very widely distributed through coastal and inland parts of south eastern Australia.
description: A dense ground cover herb with dark green leaves and lovely purple flowers.
cultivation: A mat forming plant for those difficult shady sites or under trees and shrubs. Tolerates many soil types, coastal and inland areas. Can also tolerate some drier periods.

range: Distributed in rainforests of south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: A small tree with attractive foliage, fragrant pinkish white flowers and showy fruit.
cultivation: A rainforest species, so best grown in areas with adequate moisture. Not as hardy as some plants, but very attractive in the garden once established. Choose a shady protected position.

range: Grows in easterly areas from North Queensland to central New South Wales.
description: Dense shrub up to 2m. Black seeds attract birds with red aril.
cultivation: Grow in a sunny position with adequate moisture available. Tolerant of wind and salt air.

range: Stronghold on north east New South Wales, stretching up into eastern Queensland north to Mackay. Occurs mainly east of the Dividing Range, but found inland near the NSW Qld border.
description: Small shrubby tree to 7m. Interesting leaves with uneven margins. Black fruits coupled with bright red aril as an attractant to birds.
cultivation: Grow in part shade on well drained soil. Tolerant of some drought but only light frosts.

range: Main population present in inland parts of south east Queensland.
description: A tree growing to 10m with very interesting hairy bark on the main trunk. Needle like foliage and cones provide resources for numerous birds.
cultivation: Can grow in a range of soil conditions but needs good drainage in areas of high moisture content.

range: Widely distributed along east Australia through to Tasmania. Despite it's large range, this species is being cleared heavily for urban development.
description: Small to medium tree with weeping green needle like foliage and seasonal cones which are a valuable food source for Glossy Black Cockatoo. Plants are either male or female, so for best fruit crop it is recommended to have a couple of each.
cultivation: Versatile species making an attractive screen. Shallow root systems that can tolerate poor soils but grows best in soil with some drainage.

range: Grows widely throughout south eastern Australia.
description: A small tree to 15m with needle like foliage and seed-bearing cones.
cultivation: Grows in a range of soils with fast early growth slowing as it matures. Moderately tolerant of drought and salt air.

range: Grows through eastern Australia from far north Queensland into South Australia.
description: Large tree up to 20m with attractive bark, foliage and fruit.
cultivation: Enjoys full sun and regular watering in early stages. Drought tolerant once established. Tolerates clay soils and fairly frost resistant.

range: Isolated populations in south east Queensland, north east New South Wales and south east New South Wales.
description: Large tree to 25m with large attractive red flowers.
cultivation: Grows best in loamy soil in a sunny or partially shaded position. Frost tolerant.

range: Grows throughout rainforests in eastern Australia with hotspots in north Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Grows to between 1-2m. Large green heart shaped leaves. White flowers are fragrant and red fruits attract birds.
cultivation: Requires a moist position out of direct sunlight.

range: Native to Queensland, Northern Territory and New South Wales. Widespread and fairly common.
description: A short tree with a brown or grey covering of fine hairs on young buds. Trunk is distinctively mottled greyish. Flowers are strong-smelling. Fruit is globose and black.
cultivation: Grows in a range of conditions. If moist and warm it will grow larger.

range: Grows in rainforests and wet eucalypt forest throughout eastern Australia.
description: Attractive green shrub with broad green leaves. Grows up to 2m.
cultivation: Shade and moisture loving, but requires reasonable drainage. Will tolerate some direct sun, or ideal as a potted plant.

range: Distributed in eastern parts from central New South Wales  to north Queensland.
description: Attractive but prickly shrub with fragrant white flowers and red fruits. Perfect nesting habitat for small birds.
cultivation: Hardy and adaptable but best grown in part shade.

range: Found almost exclusively in eastern Queensland.
description: Despite having a relatively short main trunk, this species has very long fronds to 5 m in length.
cultivation: Grows in shady positions with adequate moisture.

range: Very common in eastern New South Wales, extending into south east Queensland.
description: Large tree to 30m tall.
cultivation: Grow in full sun with moderate drainage.

range: A common eucalypt family tree that grows from Grafton into south east Queensland.
description: A large tree to 20m with a spreading canopy and fluffy white flowers.
cultivation: Grow in full sun in a range of soil types.

range: Very common in eastern New South Wales, extending into south east Queensland.
description: Medium to large tree to 20m.
cultivation: Enjoys full sun in a range of soil types. Tolerates light frost.

range: Largely restricted to north east New South Wales and south east Queensland. Small numbers around Melbourne.
description: Medium to large tree to 20m.
cultivation: Grows in sandy sols in full or partial sun.

range: Largely restricted to north east New South Wales and south east Queensland.
description: A large shrub to approximately 6m. Broad leaves that are red in early stages and flowers that are white and bell shaped.
cultivation: Plant in a semi-shaded position as an understorey plant.

range: Coastal range from south east Queensland south through Victoria and Tasmania.
description: An evergreen heath shrub to 2m with yellow flowers in Winter to Spring.
cultivation: Grows best in sandier soils that experience wet and dry spells. Plant in full sun. Annual pruning improves density of foliage.

range: Coastal range from south east Queensland and northern New South Wales.
description: An evergreen heath shrub to 2m with yellow flowers.
cultivation: Grows best in sandier soils that experience wet and dry spells. Plant in full sun. Annual pruning improves density of foliage.

range: Found in coastal areas through most of Queensland into northern New South Wales.
description: A drier rainforest tree that grows to 15m with ornamental leaves and small red fruits.
cultivation: Very hardy and tolerant of dry, harsh conditions.

range: Natural distribution in satellite populations in south east Queensland and far north Queensland.
description: A tall tree growing 30-45 metres in height, with a straight, rough-barked trunk, and a very distinctive symmetrical, dome-shaped crown.
cultivation: Suited to large areas that will allow for the growth of a large tree.

range: Grows in warm rainforests through Eastern Australia.
description: An often emergent tree reaching 50m in height. Strange, prehistoric-looking tree with staggered branches and often many bare limbs and tufts of foliage at the end of branches.
cultivation: Grow in an area appropriate for how large this species gets. Rural blocks adjacent to rainforest are ideal.

range: Found in the rainforests of south east Queensland, north east New South Wales and far north Queensland.
description: A medium-sized tree to about 15 metres tall with large flowers of white and pink.
cultivation: Suits well drained soil, preferably in semi shade but it will tolerate full sun. Once established it should tolerate extended dry periods but would benefit from additional watering during those times.

synonyms: Bangalow palm, king palm, Illawara palm, piccabben, piccabeen
range: Grows in rainforests among moist soils often along creek lines or riverine systems through south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: A 20-25m tall palm tree with an enlarged trunk base. Large bunches of small lilac or pink flowers, followed by round red fruits.
cultivation: Grows in moist areas with shade.

range: Coastal zones of Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Tree to 15m with new growth that is bronze-pink, foliage is dense.
cultivation: Hardy in full sun with adequate water, otherwise, prefers shade when young.

range: Fairly common throughout eastern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: An erect fern bearing bright or lime-green, shiny fronds radiating from the base. Grows as an epiphyte in rainforest areas.
cultivation: Grows best in moist but well drained conditions with filtered light. Tolerates moderate frost.

range: Restricted to south east Queensland.
description: An epiphytic fern (growing on trees) with leaves to 130cm long.
cultivation: Perfect for cool areas with plenty of moisture.

range: Large populations in south east Queensland and northern Western Australia.
description: A small tree to 10m with interesting leaves and small white flowers.
cultivation: Drought hardy, but tolerates only the lightest frosts when it is young.

range: Largely distributed in the greater south eastern Queensland region.
description: Small to medium tree to 25m with glossy green leaves and bright orange fruits. Ideal shade tree for the garden.
cultivation: Enjoys full sun in many soil types. Tolerates light frost.

range: Found only in south-east Queensland from Fraser Island to the border with New South Wales and down to Valla. Fairly common
description: A semi-prostrate shrub growing up to 50cm in height but much more extensive laterally. Small white flowers followed by white berries.
cultivation: A hardy species that grows in a range of soils and tolerates salt air.

range: Found in coastal areas through most of Queensland into northern New South Wales.
description: A robust climber with a woody stem and glossy green foliage. Beautiful flowers in Spring.
cultivation: Ideal as a ground cover or climber on structures that can withstand the weight of a heavier vine. Grows best with adequate water available but hardy otherwise.

range: Largely restricted to north east New South Wales and south east Queensland.
description: A robust climber with a woody stem and glossy green foliage. White flowers in Spring.
cultivation: Ideal as a ground cover or climber on structures that can withstand the weight of a heavier vine. Grows best with adequate water available but hardy otherwise.

range: Found in eastern New South Wales and south east Queensland.
description: A tall grass that has creamy feather like seed heads.
cultivation: Plant in full sun or part shade. Tolerant of most soils.

range: Found in wet eucalypt and rainforests of eastern parts along Queensland and New South Wales coasts.
description: A medium sized tree to 8m that starts with a multi-stemmed growth form before deciding on one main stem. Bunches of small white fluffy flowers in autumn. Highly aromatic oils found in the leaves.
cultivation: Grow in at least part shade, even full shade is tolerated. Plant in well drained soil and give adequate watering.

range: Found along the eastern side of Queensland and New South Wales.
description: A small shrub or tree with glossy green leaves and small white flowers.
cultivation: Enjoys a sunny position that gets adequate moisture.

range: Found from mid Queensland coastal areas to southern New South Wales.
description: An aquatic plant that forms dense mats with small white flowers.
cultivation: Can be grown in very damp positions in the garden.

range: Grows in coastal areas in north Queensland, south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Shrub to 1m with weeping foliage.
cultivation: Naturally occurring in coastal heath, this species prefers sandy soils and full sun.

range: Coastal species of south east Queensland through to central coast New South Wales.
description: Upright grassy looking sedge with golden brown flowers at the ends of the stems. Grows to 1-1.5m in height.
cultivation: Grows in most soils, but naturally occurs in sandier soils. Performs bets in full sun. Tolerates some poor drainage.

range: Coastal heath species found in south east Queensland and east New South Wales.
description: A small tree to 8m with attractive foliage and large lemon yellow flower spikes followed by unusual seed heads.
cultivation: Ideal garden plant but requires adequate drainage, so sandy soils are best. Full sun and frost tolerant.

range: Coastal species of Banksia often seen growing in sand dunes from mid north Queensland south to Victoria.
description: Can grow to be a large tree or be trimmed to smaller size. Green leaves with a white underside and lemon yellow flower heads.
cultivation: A fast-growing tree suitable for coastal plantings where resistance to wind and salt exposure is important. It prefers sandy acidic soils and is moderately drought and frost tolerant.

range: Grows in a variety of habitats including open woodland, swamp margins, shrubland, coastal slopes from New South Wales south coast to central Queensland coast.
description: A shrub that grows to about 3m with dark green leaves and lemon yellow flower heads followed by woody seed heads.
cultivation: Ideal for gardens on sandy soil. Prefers well drained soil but benefits from adequate watering. Plant in full sun for best results.

range: Coastal swamp species found in far north Queensland, south east Queensland through to central coast New South Wales.
description: Branching shrub with large hard leaves and golden flower heads. New leaf growth is hairy and attractive golden red in colour.
cultivation: Will thrive in a variety of soils but is ideal for the damp corner. If adequate watering is available, it will tolerate drier areas. Full sun is required for good flowering.

range: Coastal species of Banksia often seen growing in sand dunes from Victoria north to south east Queensland.
description: A shrub to 3m with gnarled bark, interesting foliage and lemon yellow flower spikes. Woody seed heads develop after flowering.
cultivation: Ideal garden plant but requires adequate drainage, so sandy soils are best. Full sun and frost tolerant.

range: Found primarily in coastal districts along the subtropical Queensland and New South Wales coast.
description: Multi-branching shrub to around 2 or 3m in height. Large red-golden flower heads that glow in sunlight at dawn and dusk.
cultivation: All cultivars require full sun and well-drained soils.

range: Relatively restricted range in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland hinterland rainforest.
description: Medium tree to 8m in cultivation. Stunning yellow flower spikes and bushy green foliage.
cultivation: Plant in part shade. Tolerant to light frost.

range: Grows in coastal areas from southern New South Wales to south east Queensland.
description: Attractive shrub to 1.5m with pretty pink flowers.
cultivation: Will grow in part sun, preferably in the morning. Enjoys adequate watering. Light pruning of green growth recommended after flowering but not too much.

range: Grows throughout the coastal areas of the southern half of Australia
description: A small native reed with bluish greyish cylindrical foliage and red-brown seed heads.
cultivation: A wetland species that grows in very damp or wet spots. Ideal for the edges of ponds or boggy spots.

range: Grows throughout the coastal areas of most of Australia.
description: Bright green rush to 1m with reddish brown spikelets.
cultivation: A wetland species that grows in very damp or wet spots. Ideal for the edges of ponds or boggy spots.

range: Coastal range from south east Queensland and northern New South Wales.
description: A grass like plant with red and gold bell shaped flowers.
cultivation: Prefers moist, well drained soils preferably sandy loam. Some protection from full sun needed but not ideally grown in heavy shade. It is tolerant of at least moderate frosts. It is very suitable for growing in pots.

range: Found throughout Australia in suitable habitat.
description: An erect, clustered fern with numerous pinnate fronds extending to 60 or 70cm long.
cultivation: Grows in shade or part shade positions. Enjoys very moist positions.

range: Coastal range from south east Queensland and northern New South Wales.
description: Small shrub to 1m with hot pink fragrant flowers.
cultivation: Grow in full or part sun in well drained soil but with an adequate supply of water.

range: Coastal Queensland from Cairns south to far north eastern New South Wales.
description: Small to medium tree to 18m with attractive green foliage that is tinged red when young.
cultivation: Best in sheltered site in part to full shade.

range: Widespread in suitable forest across eastern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Tall deciduous tree to 40m. Leaves are large and glossy. Flowers are bright red.
cultivation: Quite slow growing and semi-deciduous. Grows in a variety of soil conditions, with some tolerance to droughts and frosts.

range: Fairly restricted to eastern parts of Queensland.
cultivation: Suitable for hot dry sites. Plant in full sun. Suitable around suburban homes as it has a non-invasive root system

range: Native to south east Queensland.
description: Very attractive small tree with broad green lobed leaves, pink flowers in Spring and unusual fruit.
cultivation: Plant in moist but well drained soil in part or full sun. Protect from frost and drought in early stages.

range: Grows in coastal areas from southern New South Wales to south east Queensland.
description: A medium sized tree to 20m with large leaves and lowers that are deep pink in colour.
cultivation: Hardy in a range of conditions. It is partly to completely deciduous before flowering, and tolerant of a range of soils.

range: Grows through much of eastern Australia including inland areas.
description: A medium tree to 20m with semi deciduous habit. Flowers are white on the exterior and red inside.
cultivation: Slower growing species but tolerant of a range of conditions. Plant in full sun with reasonably well drained soils.

range: Confined to southern Queensland ranging from the coast far inland to Charleville.
description: A striking tree growing to 18m in height. The trunk is uniquely bottle-shaped; grossly swollen at the base and tapering to a narrower diameter. The flowers are yellowish in colour and bell-shaped, often concealed by foliage.
cultivation: Grows in dry, heavy clay and silty substrates in open, often droughted regions.

range: An extremely rare tree confined solely to 161 plants in council reserves and roadside remnants along the Albert and Pimpama river catchments.
description: An imposing tree growing to around 30m in height. Has a slightly swollen base when mature, as with other bottletrees. Flowers are creamy-green in colour, bell-shaped and form in clusters at the ends of branches.
cultivation: Grows in soils characteristic of rainforest margins. Relatively free draining soil with good organic matter.

range: Natural range throughout south eastern Australia.
description: Perennial herb with very attractive purple daisy like flowers.
cultivation: Grows in range of conditions and soils. Benefits from light pruning after flowering events.

synonyms: Scrub Ironbark, Grey Birch, Brown Birch
range: Coastal range from south east Queensland and central New South Wales.
description: Tall shrub or small tree up to 10m with small flowers.
cultivation: A rainforest plant that responds well to part shade and well drained moist soils.

range: Natural population stronghold throughout eastern Queensland.
description: Tall shrub or small tree up to 10m with small flowers.
cultivation: Relatively easy to grow in areas with a natural tendency for dry rainforest vegetation.

range: Widespread across Australia except the far north.
description: Small herb with pretty globes of purple flowers on a stalk sprouting from a rosette of leaves at ground level.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in relatively well drained soil.

range: Natural range throughout south eastern Australia.
description: Bright yellow flowers emerging from strappy green leaves. Grows to less than 1m.
cultivation: Adaptable to a range of conditions, but retains most green growth if given adequate water. Plant in full or part sun.

range: Found in coastal areas in south east and south west of Australia.
description: A perennial herb with grass like leaves and small white flowers on stalks up to 60cm tall.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in relatively well drained soil.

range: Extensive distribution through north east Australia.
description: Tall shrub to 5m with masses of small white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full sun in well drained soil. Prune after flowering to keep foliage dense and ensure good flowering.

range: Coastal range from south east Queensland and northern New South Wales.
description: A robust climbing plant with evergreen foliage and flushes of purple flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun with adequate support to hold a heavy climber.

range: Hotspot of distribution along eastern New South Wales coast, extending into south east Queensland.
description: Small shrubby tree to 10m with attractive dark green leaves with serrated edges and small white pom pom style flowers.
cultivation: A rainforest species, plant in positions that receive adequate moisture and are not exposed to frosts.

range: Widely distributed in sporadic clusters throughout Australia.
description: Medium sized tree to 30m with a characteristic conifer look.
cultivation: Grows in part sun in a range of soil conditions providing there is adequate supply of moisture.

range: Widely distributed in sporadic clusters throughout southern Australia.
description: Medium sized tree to 30m with a characteristic conifer look.
cultivation: Drought tolerant and adapted for heavy soils. Grows best in full sun.

range: Widely distributed though coastal rainforests and wet eucalypt forests of eastern Australia
description: Feathery large leaved fern to 1.5m high.
cultivation: Hardy fern tolerant of a range of conditions. Best if planted in part to full shade.

range: Naturally occurs in south eastern Australia and a patch of south western Australia.
description: Smallish shrub to 1m with delicate foliage and pretty small star shaped flowers.
cultivation: Not very common in cultivation but an ideal garden plant. It is adapted to local conditions so best to source stock that is native to the area. Grow in full sun in well drained soil that is tending to acid pH.

range: Coastal distribution through most of the northern Australia coastline.
description: Ground cover or climbing vine with large green leaves and purple pea flowers.
cultivation: Perfect for beachfront gardens or any well drained sandy soil. Plant in full sun.

range: Found throughout tropical Queensland and along the coast into New South Wales as far as the Hunter River.
description: A medium-sized shrub with grey bark. Attractive leaves and beautiful white flowers with long stamens.
cultivation: Prefers part sunny aspect and soil with reasonable drainage. Young plants have spiky leaves that become soft when plant ages.

range: Large distribution through inland eastern Australia.
description: A small tree to 8m with densely leaved crown and large white flowers that develop into fruits commonly eaten by aboriginal people to this day.
cultivation: Tolerant to all conditions except poor drainage. Best suited to drier sunny positions.

range: Frequent across Australia.
description: An attractive clumping sedge to 1m with green foliage and red-brown seed heads.
cultivation: Ideal as a border or around water bodies or in damp positions. Grows well in drier positions also.

range: East coast distribution through parts of Queensland and most of New South Wales.
description: Upright sedge to 60cm with narrow green strappy leaves. Variegated cultivars available.
cultivation: Ideal as a border planted in full sun and well drained soil.

range: Coastal districts in the far south east of the continent with northern most limit in south east Queensland.
description: Large densely tufted clumping sedge to 1m with strappy green leaves and attractive seed heads. Provides habitat for birds and frogs when planted in a hedge style.
cultivation: Tolerant of most conditions, but best planted in full sun in boggy conditions.

range: Coastal districts in the far south east of the continent with northern most limit in south east Queensland.
description: Large loosely tufted clumping sedge to 1m with strappy green leaves and attractive seed heads. Provides habitat for birds and frogs when planted in a hedge style.
cultivation: Tolerant of most conditions, but best planted in full sun in boggy conditions.

range: Coastal distribution from central Queensland to southern New South Wales
description: Creeping succulent with triangular leaves and hot pink flowers.
cultivation: Grows best in sandy soils in full sun but tolerant of many conditions. Ideal as a  ground cover in garden beds.

range: Very small range in far south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Low creeping vine of the rainforest undergrowth. Important food plant of the Pink Underwing Moth.
cultivation: Grows best in part or full shade. Ideal for backyard rainforest plots in the region.

range: Rare, only found growing from Brunswick, New South Wales north to the Gold Coast hinterland.
description: An evergreen tree to 20m. Showy yellow flowers.
cultivation: Plant in a sunny well drained position not subject to frosts.

range: Relatively common tree found in Queensland’s coastal belt and in north-eastern New South Wales.
description: A medium tree to 30m with a narrow trunk and pale, smooth, blotched bark.
cultivation: Ideal species for semi-rural blocks in wet eucalypt or rainforest zones. Suited to fertile, well drained soils in full sun. Sensitive to frost.

range: Naturally occurs in rainforests of the Australian east coast.
description: Medium sized tree to 30m with attractive green foliage and small white flowers on spikes.
cultivation: Best suited to semi-shaded positions in well drained soil.

range: Range extends from central Queensland through New South Wales, inland from coast.
description: Medium to large tree to 20m with needle like foliage and attractive woody cones.
cultivation: Grows best in heavier clay soils, does not flourish in sandy soils. Prefers full sun.

range: Large range from top end in Northern Territory through Queensland south to Victoria and Tasmania with populations becoming scattered at southern most limits.
cultivation: Grows in full or part sun and tolerates drought and inundation once established. A large tree so requires adequate space, but ideal for sites with natural waterways in occurrence.

range: Large range from top end in Northern Territory through Queensland south to New South Wales.
description: A small to medium tree to 10-15m with weeping needle like foliage.
cultivation: Grows in sandy soils in full sun. Tolerant of salt and wind.

range: Predominantly a coastal species of New South Wales and South Australia, extending into south east Queensland but not common in Victoria.
description: A small to medium tree with needle like foliage and small cones for fruit. Plants are either male or female, so plant multiple plants for fruit production.
cultivation: Grows in damp positions, especially swampy areas. Plant in full sun.

range: Coastal distribution from Gulf of Carpentaria to southern coast to New South Wales.
description: Small tree in cultivation to 6m with rich green foliage.
cultivation: Needs free draining soil and sun or part shade.

range: Stronghold of range through coastal New South Wales extending minorly into south east Queensland.
description: Medium sized tree to 15m, but only 5m in cultivation, with a mottled trunk and many white flowers in Spring and Summer
cultivation: Plant in full sun but best suited to soils that tend to me moist.

range: Drier rainforest tree through much of the southern half of Queensland in coastal areas.
description: Fairly tall tree to 25m with attractive foliage and white flowers.
cultivation: Grows best in sun but protected from harsher weather conditions.

range: Widespread and common across the south east Queensland region.
description: Small herb with bright yellow flowers.
cultivation: Ideal as a groundcover. Semi-annual in growth, so may need replacing.

range: A rainforest tree extending from far north Queensland to south coast New South Wales.
description: A medium sized tree with aromatic glossy green leaves with wavy margins and white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full sun to part shade . Best suited to areas with adequate rainfall, or in gardens that receive adequate watering.

range: Widely distributed though coastal rainforests and wet eucalypt forests of eastern Australia
description: A woody climber that occurs in the understorey of wet eucalypt and rainforest.
cultivation: Grows in loamy soil types in shadier positions. Ideal as a climber or a groundcover.

range: Stronghold of distribution in eastern New South Wales with clusters of occurrence in southern and northern Queensland.
description: A large rainforest tree with large glossy green leaves and flowers that develop into bird attracting fruits.
cultivation: Best suited to larger blocks that are adjacent to rainforest areas.

range: Relatively restricted range in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland hinterland rainforest.
description: Small shrubby tree to 6m with small leaves and spikes. Bears fruits in autumn and winter.
cultivation: Slow growing, so best planted as a relatively mature plant (as opposed to planting from seed). Plant in part shade with adequately nutrient rich soil.

range: Common through most parts of eastern  Queensland.
description: A small rainforest tree to 6m high with bunches of small white flowers.
cultivation: Grow in nutrient rich well drained soils in part shade.

range: Found only in south-east Queensland and north-east New South Wales. Locally common.
description: Small tree or shrub. Flowers grow in dense clusters. Fruit is a bristly brown-green capsule
cultivation: Grows best in full sun with well drained soil.

range: Common through north east New South Wales extending into south east Queensland.
description: A small to medium-sized palm-like plant to 5m high. The main stem is often branched. Green strap like leaves, purple flowers followed by bright red fruits.
cultivation: Grows in most soils and part shade. Not tolerant of heavy frost.

range: Common throughout southern Queensland along the coastal rainforest ranges to Lismore, New South Wales.
description: Shrub to 4m in height with a woody main stem and multiple leaves at the top. Leaves are palm like. Spikes of lilac blue flowers develop into red berries.
cultivation: Grows best in part shade in well drained soils. Many cultivars available.

range: Common through east New South Wales extending into south east Queensland with scattered populations through to north Queensland.
description: Small paper daisy with white and yellow flowers.
cultivation: Ideal garden plant with attractive daisy flowers.

range: Mid sized shrub to 2m, but usually smaller. Open habit with small leaves and red weeping tubular flowers.
Abundant in eastern Queensland and clustered populations in New South Wales and Victoria.
description: Tall tree with dimply spotted bark and lemon scented leaves.
cultivation: Highly tolerant to a range of conditions but due to it's size best planted on blocks that can accommodate larger trees.

range: Found across Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland. Predominantly near coast.
description: A tall tree to 30m with persistent reddish-brown, tessellated bark.
cultivation: This species is a tall and requires space, but fast-growing tree and is easy to maintain in a garden once established.

range: Distributed through most of eastern Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Large tree to 30m high with persistent tessellated bark that is reddish-brown in colour.
cultivation: Suited to larger gardens. Grows in a variety of conditions.

range: Found in southern Queensland and northern New South Wales. Local.
description: A tree to 30m high with persistent grey-black tessellated bark at the base of the trunk and clear, white-grey bark above. Clusters of white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full sun with enough space to accommodate the large size it can reach.

range: Large range through eastern Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Medium to large tree to 25m with flaky bark and creamy white flowers in summer and autumn.
cultivation: Grows best in drier areas in full sun. Needs adequate space as per other eucalypts.

range: Large range through eastern Queensland to northern Western Australia.
description: A clump-forming, thick, fleshy plant growing to 1m tall. Leaves are long and strap-like. Flowers white with drooping petals and stamens that reach 7cm high bearing pink, red or purple filaments.
cultivation: Plant in moist soils but can tolerate many soil types. Grows best in part shade.

range: Native to coastal swamps of New South Wales and southern Queensland.
description: A clump-forming, thick, fleshy plant growing to 50cm tall. Leaves are long and strap-like. Flowers white with drooping petals and stamens that reach 7cm high bearing pink, red or purple filaments.
cultivation: Plant in moist soils but can tolerate many soil types. Grows best in part shade.

range: Distributed through most of eastern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: A small rainforest tree to 15m high with small white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full sun in well drained soil with adequate nutrients.

range: Eastern Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Small rainforest tree to 10m with glossy green leaves and blue fruits that attract birds.
cultivation: Prefers a moist free draining protected site in part shade when young.

range: Relatively restricted range in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland hinterland rainforest.
description: Tall slender rainforest tree to 30m with slightly buttressed trunk.
cultivation: Prefers moist well drained soil.

synonyms: White Sycamore, Rib Fruited Pepperberry, She-beech, Sycamore, White Walnut, Bastard Sycamore, North Queensland Purple Laurel
range: Occurs through most coastal areas of Northern Territory, Queensland and New South Wales.
description: A large tree to 30m that is an important food source for multiple bird and butterfly species.
cultivation: Plant in full sun or part shade. Ideal for rainforest plots.

range: Relatively restricted range in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland hinterland rainforest.
description: Densely foliaged rainforest tree to 40m with bird attracting fruits.
cultivation: Plant in areas naturally tending to rainforest communities with enough space to accommodate the large size it can reach.

range: Common along the New South Wales and Queensland rainforest coasts.
description: Small to medium rainforest tree with rich green foliage and purple-black fruits.
cultivation: Grow in well drained soils or even sand. Ideal for coastal positions.

range: Common in subtropical Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Small or medium-sized tree to 10m. Dense evergreen foliage with very small flowers that develop into orange fruits.
cultivation: Popular street tree. Very hardy once established.

range: Highly restricted range in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland hinterland rainforest.
description: Small rainforest tree to 6m with wavy edged green leaves that  are red when young and pink fruits that attract birds.
cultivation: Prefers moist well drained soil. Perfect for smaller rainforest style gardens.

range: Common along the north east New South Wales and Queensland rainforest coasts.
description: Medium tree to 20m with attractive green foliage and bright orange fruits.
cultivation: A hardy, small tree with spreading crown creating good shade. Hardy but grows slower in especially dry areas.

range: Found in sub tropical and cool temperate rainforests from central Queensland to Tasmania.
description: Large tree-fern to 20m, but usually less. Fronds reach 3m long from main stem.
cultivation: Tree-ferns grow best in high humidity and high soil moisture conditions.

range: Found in warm gullies in coastal rainforest in isolated populations in north Queensland and from south east Queensland to the south coast of New South Wales.
description: Often very large fern with a woody, heavily scarred trunk of stringy tissue and old leaf joints. Fronds reach 5m long with green leaflets.
cultivation: Tree-ferns grow best in high humidity and high soil moisture conditions.

range: Found in sub tropical and cool temperate rainforests in south east Queensland, Victoria and Tasmania.
description: Large slender tree-fern to 20m, but usually less. Fronds reach 3m long from main stem.
cultivation: Tree-ferns grow best in high humidity and high soil moisture conditions.

range: A very common grass across Queensland's forests and also found in New South Wales and Victoria.
description: A perennial grass growing to about 1m in height.
cultivation: Grows on a range of soils, even relatively poor soils.

range: Large range throughout the eastern half of Australia.
description: Large tussock forming perennial sedge to 1.8m. Very good for creating frog and waterbird habitat.
cultivation: Hardy if sufficient water is available. Perfect for creek lines and around ponds.

range: Found in scattered populations through eastern Australia and less commonly in the top end and south west of the continent.
description: Tussock forming perennial sedge to 0.6m.
cultivation: Hardy if sufficient water is available. Perfect for creek lines and around ponds.

range: A very rare plant restricted entirely to the Queensland-New South Wales border around the Tweed Valley area.
description: A small, sparsely-vegetated tree with a few branches. Flowers are salmon-pink and fruit is a large blue-black (when ripe) plum.
cultivation: A rainforest species, so best grown in areas with adequate moisture. Not as hardy as some plants, but very attractive in the garden once established. Choose a shady protected position.

range: A very rare plant restricted entirely to the Brunswick Tweed region.
description: A small, sparsely-vegetated tree with a few branches. Flowers are salmon-pink and fruit is a large blue-black (when ripe) plum.
cultivation: A rainforest species, so best grown in areas with adequate moisture. Not as hardy as some plants, but very attractive in the garden once established. Choose a shady protected position.

range: Relatively restricted range in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland.
description: Shrub or small tree with weeping branches, to 14m high with bark corky.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in relatively well drained soil.

range: Common in the south eastern part of the continent.
description: Attractive shrub to 1-2m with yellow and red pea flowers. Naturally occurs in dry eucalypt forest with heath understorey.
cultivation: Plants will grow in semi shade but perform best in a well-drained sunny position which is well mulched. They respond to light pruning after flowering in the early stages of development.

range: Eastern Queensland and south to the central coast of New South Wales.
description: Bushy shrub with masses of fluffy white flowers followed by small black fruit. Flushes of delicate silky new growth. Useful for a compact hedge.
cultivation: Grows in a range of soils in sun or part shade.

range: Isolated populations in eastern New South Wales and only just extending into south east Queensland.
description: Epiphytic orchid herb that naturally occurs on Antarctic Beech trees but will grow on other plants in cultivation.
cultivation: Grows well mounted on a tree-fern or timber slab and hung in an airy shade house. However, it can also be grown successfully in a pot if the compost is free draining.

range: South eastern Queensland and south to the central coast of New South Wales.
description: Elegant orchid in white and purple varieties, forming mats of growth with mass flowering. Naturally grows on large rocks but can also grow as an epiphyte on Casuarinas.
cultivation: Popular in cultivation and is easy to grow in tropical to temperate climates. Grows on trees where branches meet the main trunk or in pots in a very loose medium such as bark mulch or specialised orchid potting mix.

range: Grows through much of the eastern part of the continent.
cultivation: Popular in cultivation and is easy to grow in tropical to temperate climates. Grows on trees where branches meet the main trunk or in pots in a very loose medium such as bark mulch or specialised orchid potting mix.

range: Found in open forest & woodland of south east Queensland.
description: Tufted clumping flax lily to 50cm tall with attractive purple flowers.
cultivation: Ideal used in rockeries and as a bordering plant. Well drained soil, can tolerate dry spells and is suitable for reasonably cold temperatures and sub tropical climates. Water during the first 8-12 weeks until the plant is established.

range: Common from Queensland to Victoria.
description: A perennial herb forming mats and tufts of long strap-like leaves. Pretty purple flowers in spikes followed by violet coloured fruits.
cultivation: Enjoys full sun and most soil conditions. Very hardy.

range: Coastal sub-tropics from southern Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: This hardy flax lilly has strappy green evergreen leaves and shiny bright blue bunches of fruit. Can serve many purposes as a ground cover and border plant.
cultivation: Enjoys full sun and well drained soil, but hardy nonetheless. Once established this plant needs virtually no additional watering except in extended periods of drought.

range: Several clustered populations in the south east of the continent.
description: Shrub to 2m with pretty yellow pea flowers.
cultivation: Plant in sandier soils in full sun. Grows best in areas that get waterlogged from time to time.

range: Eastern New South Wales extending into south east Queensland.
description: This slender tree is crowned with large velvety leaves when young. The fruit of Native Tamarind is yellow-brown and hairy.
cultivation: Rainforest adapted species so best planted in semi shade with an adequate water supply.

range: Very rare, found only from the Richmond River area of New South Wales north to the Queensland border on the Gold Coast.
description: A small tree to 10m high with a dense crown providing good shade. Small flowers develop into larger fruit with red aril.
cultivation: Plant in part shade. Remove additional stems to train into a single trunk.

range: Almost exclusively in coastal dry rainforest areas of the southern half of Queensland.
description: Medium tree to 20m with attractive foliage and yellow furry fruits.
cultivation: Grows in full sun or part shade to form a very hardy bushy tree.

range: Sub-tropical range through eastern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Shrub to 3m with really unusual leaf shapes and seed pods that provide visual appeal like flowers normally do.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in relatively well drained soil. Plant multiple plants, ensuring both sexes have representation as plants are either male or female.

range: Common in fringing forests near rainforests from southern Queensland to central New South Wales.
description: An erect branching shrub that can reach 5m in height. Small flowers develop into interesting seed capsules that are red in colour and provide the same visual amenity as flowers usually exhibit.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in relatively well drained soil. Plant multiple plants, ensuring both sexes have representation as plants are either male or female.

range: Range covers almost the entire continent except for the top end and northern Western Australia.
description: Shrub to 3m with dense growth and seed pods that provide visual appeal like flowers normally do.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in relatively well drained soil. Plant multiple plants, ensuring both sexes have representation as plants are either male or female.

range: Hotspot of distribution along eastern New South Wales coast, extending to far north Queensland at lower densities.
description: Attractive fern with green and red-orange frond growth. Fronds grow to 50cm from base in spreading clumps.
cultivation: Grows best in shady conditions and in acidic soil, with high organic composition. Plants like a good level of moisture, but also require well-drained conditions to prevent sweating problems.

range: Large range through most of the eastern coastline of the continent.
description: Small creeping fern to  40cm high. New growth has an attractive red-bronze colour.
cultivation: Plant in part or full shade in damp areas of the garden. Tolerates poorer soils, but performs best with some enriched organic matter.

range: Restricted largely to a few igneous outcrops around the Mt. Warning caldera and northwards to the Gold Coast hinterland.
description: An enormous perennial herb growing into a giant rosette with a central spike featuring the flowers. Flowers are in a  spike arrangement and are red in colour.
cultivation: Because this plant is adapted to relatively dry conditions it makes a low maintenance and long-lived garden plant.

range: Stronghold distribution in New South Wales coast extending into the far south east Queensland hinterland.
description: Shrubby tree to 30m with compact crown and distinct sweet fragrance. Small white flowers.
cultivation: Fairly fast in moist well drained soil, but adapts to most soils and conditions.

range: Eastern distribution from central New South Wales into south east Queensland.
description: Medium tree to 30m tall with rich green foliage, cream to mauve flowers and reddish fruits.
cultivation: Slow but hardy in well drained slightly acid soils, though slightly frost sensitive. Prefers a protected site when young.

range: Found in north-eastern New South Wales, north to the Cape York Peninsula, Queensland.
description: Large shrub or medium tree with red new growth and glossy green mature leaves. Fragrant white leaves.
cultivation: Plant in well drained to most soils in full sun or part shade.

range: Largely restricted to rainforests of western Queensland but also found in suitable remnants in north-eastern New South Wales.
description: A rainforest tree that has attractive bark, foliage and fruit. Once established it is fast growing.
cultivation: Perfect for areas adjoining rainforest and larger sized gardens. Will not tolerate frost.

synonyms: Blueberry Ash, Whitewood, Grey Carabeen, Freckled Oliveberry, Grey Carrobeen
range: Naturally occurs from north Queensland through to south New Sales Wales.
description: Small tree to 6m suitable for screening and windbreaks, attractive green foliage and pretty white flowers.
cultivation: Bushy tree for moist well drained soil.

range: Common across eastern seaboard of Australia, including Tasmania.
description: A shrub growing to 4m in height. Flowers are white, rarely pink and fruit is a globular blue berry.
cultivation: Popular plant for gardens, preferring sunny positions but also tolerating shade.

range: Found in north-eastern New South Wales and south east Queensland.
description: Small to medium-sized tree to 12m with coppery young growth and attractive red fruits.
cultivation: Plant in full sun or part shade in well drained soils. Perfect for areas near rainforest.

range: Natural range through south eastern Australia.
description: Mauve flowers on stalks rising from a green grass like base. A perennial herb, which dies down during autumn and emerges in late winter to flower in summer.
cultivation: Ideally used as a rockery plant in an open, sunny position. Most soils seem to be suitable provided they are well drained.

range: Restricted range from north east New South Wales into south east Queensland.
description: Deciduous tree to 10m from drier rainforest with attractive orange-red flowers.
cultivation: Grows best in a well drained sunny position.

range: Large range through the northern half of the continent, tending to the east.
description: A small to intermediate growing deciduous tree to 8m with unusual broad-winged leaflets. Bears open red pea-shaped flowers
cultivation: Grows best in a well drained sunny position.

range: Eastern distribution from south New South Wales into north east Queensland.
description: Large tree reaching 40m in height. Bark is grey and somewhat stringy. Clusters of white flowers.
cultivation: This large tree is best suited to large blocks in areas that support drier eucalypt forests.

range: Naturally occurs through much of eastern New South Wales and into south east Queensland.
description: Medium to large tree 30m with patchy grey, salmon and orange bark that sheds seasonally.
cultivation: Hardy in most sunny well drained situations.

range: Naturally occurs through much of eastern New South Wales and into south east Queensland.
description: Medium to large tree to 30m but usually 10-25m. Bunches of creamy white flowers.
cultivation: Prefers clay soils in an open, sunny position.

range: Two main centres of occurrence in north east Queensland and inland areas of southern Queensland.
description: A fast growing small to medium gum tree to 20m with strong durable timber. Grows on edges of rainforest.
cultivation: Plant in full sun in areas that lend themselves to hinterland rainforest.

range: Large range through eastern parts of the continent, except southern most regions in New South Wales and Victoria.
description: Tree to 20m with strong chunky bark and slender leaves.
cultivation: Hardy in most sunny well drained situations.

range: Stronghold in eastern New South Wales, but extending into the Gold Coast hinterland.
description: Tall tree growing to 40m. Short stocking of bark surrounds the base of the mostly smooth grey trunk. Wide dark green leaves and clusters of creamy white flowers in autumn.
cultivation: Hardy in most sunny well drained situations.

range: Naturally found through most of the eastern half of Queensland.
description: Tree to 15m high with a mallee form and showy flowers.
cultivation: Hardy in most sunny well drained situations.

range: Main hotspots around the rainforests of far north Queensland and south east Queensland into north east New South Wales.
description: Large tree to 50m. Amazing silvery grey trunk that stretches straight up to the crown of green foliage.
cultivation: This large tree is best suited to large blocks in areas that support wet eucalypt or rainforest.

range: Found throughout Queensland in suitable habitat, often montane, and in a few scattered sites in New South Wales.
description: A smooth-barked gum tree to about 20m. Bark is patchy, matte grey-brown in colour with large patches. Clusters of whit flowers.
cultivation: Will grow in a range of conditions, including poor nutrient soils

range: Fairly common in suitable habitat in southern Queensland and northern New South Wales reaching relatively far inland.
description: A tree growing to 20m with thick, ridged grey-black bark that is very durable and hard.
cultivation: A drought tolerant species that enjoys full sun. Relatively tolerant of frosts.

range: Stronghold of population in south eastern Australia with isolated hotspots in south east Queensland.
description: A medium to large sized tree, growing to 30m with a sprawling crown. The branches often have a gnarled twisting form.
cultivation: Hardy in most soils in full sun or part shade.

range: Range extends from south east Queensland to south east New South Wales.
description: Large tree reaching 40m in height. Bark is persistent and reddish-brown in colour, peeling in strings. Clusters of white flowers.
cultivation: A versatile eucalypt that grows in a range of conditions. A large tree that will require adequate space.

range: Common gum forest component species along the New South Wales and Queensland coastal belt.
description: A tall tree to 70m with persistent grey-brown bark on full trunk which can be fibrous or stringy. Clusters of white flowers followed by gumnuts.
cultivation: Grows in drier areas in a range of soils. A large tree that will require adequate space, but a beautiful addition if this is feasible.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: Tree to 25m high with stringy park and white flowers.
cultivation: Grows in sandy soils in full to part sun.

range: Found along the coastal lowlands of Queensland and New South Wales, locally common.
description: A slender tree to 40m. Bark is smooth and matte in texture with patchy slates of grey-brown shedding bark. After shedding bark the trunks are a stunning salmon colour.
cultivation: Enjoys semi damp sites with poor nutrients. A large tree that needs space, but a worthy addition if you have room.

range: Found in coastal regions of southern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Tree to 15m high with pale grey or yellowish bark covered in 'scribbles' made by the caterpillars of micro-moths.
cultivation: Grows in sandy soils in full to part sun.

range: Natural range through much of the eastern seaboard.
description: Tall tree to 40m with ruddy brown stringy bark.
cultivation: Grows best in reasonably fertile soils in full sun with adequate drainage.

range: Found in coastal regions of southern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Tree to 25m high with chunky bark and white flowers.
cultivation: Naturally adapted to coastal heath, which is usually characterised by moist sandy soils. Plant in similar conditions with full sun.

range: Found in coastal regions of southern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Tall tree to 30m in cultivation but taller in the natural environment. Smooth powdery grey bark.
cultivation: The species is frost tolerant, moderately drought tolerant and considered slightly salt tolerant. Grows well in clay soils of either the sandy or loamy variety.

range: Locally common from northern New South Wales into Queensland.
description: Tree reaching 40m in height. Bark is smooth with white-grey and buff-coloured flakes. Clusters of white  flowers.
cultivation: Grows best on sandy soils that have regular water. A large tree that will require adequate space.

range: Found in coastal regions of southern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Medium to large tree to 30m but usually 10-25m. Bunches of creamy white flowers.
cultivation: Fast, hardy & adapts to most well drained sites.

range: Found across eastern Australia from Queensland to northern Victoria.
description: Tall tree to 50m or more with smooth greyish-blue bark and clusters of white flowers.
cultivation: One of the most abundant Eucalypts throughout it's range. A large tree that will require adequate space.

range: Two main centres of occurrence in north east Queensland south eastern Queensland into north east New South Wales.
description: Tree to 25m high with stringy bark and white flowers.
cultivation: Hardy in most sunny well drained situations.

range: Fairly common in protected coastal habitats from Victoria to Queensland.
description: Small tree to 7m with glossy green leaves and attractive white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in part shade areas in most soil types.

range: Found in coastal regions of southern Australia.
description: Attractive native grass-like plant with upright growth habit to 1m and brown flower spikes throughout most of the year.
cultivation: Hardy grass suited to most soil conditions, will tolerate drought, frost and saline soils. Low maintenance and tolerant of harsh conditions, requires little care once established.

range: Common through eastern sub tropical regions.
description: A tall shrub or spreading tree with very dense hairs covering its branches and leaves. The fruit is a green globular fig which is quite small (max. 2cm long) and insignificant. The fig turns darker purple or black with maturity.
cultivation: Despite being a rainforest or creek line species, this fig will grow well in gardens.

range: Natural range through much of coastal eastern Australia to southern New South Wales.
description: A shrubby tree to 6m with coarsely textured leaves and red fruits in winter and spring.
cultivation: Despite being a rainforest or creek line species, this fig will grow well in gardens.

range: Grows in coastal rainforests and on islands from New South Wales through tropical Queensland.
description: A very large, spreading tree growing up to 60m in height and having a huge canopy. Mature trees have spectacular buttressed roots and hollow-sounding trunks that often flatten out and become massive. Fruit is a globose fig to 2.5cm, yellow turning orange with age.
cultivation: Requires space for the extensive root systems. A suitable coastal tree tolerating salt laden winds and dry, sandy soil and an excellent shade tree for parks, large gardens and open space plantings. Needs plant of room to spread both above and below ground. Avoid planting near pipes and foundations.

range: Natural range through much of coastal eastern Australia to southern New South Wales.
description: A very large, spreading tree growing up to 60m in height and having a huge canopy. Mature trees have spectacular buttressed roots and hollow-sounding trunks that often flatten out and become massive. Fruit is a globose fig to 1cm, yellow turning orange with age.
cultivation: Requires space for the extensive root systems. A suitable coastal tree tolerating salt laden winds and dry, sandy soil and an excellent shade tree for parks, large gardens and open space plantings. Needs plant of room to spread both above and below ground. Avoid planting near pipes and foundations.

range: Strongholds in the north west of the continent, with isolated representation in south east Queensland.
description: Grows to a medium shrub or small tree to 8m with very attractive leaves and fruit.
cultivation: Hardy in most sunny well drained situations.

range: Grows in coastal rainforests from southern New South Wales through tropical Queensland.
description: Attractive shade giving tree with two toned leaves and fruits to 1cm in diameter. Variable size, but rarely exceeds 10m in cultivation.
cultivation: Not as large and potentially invasive in urban settings as some other figs, but still better suited to larger blocks or for use in urban parks.

range: Large range through coastal areas of the northern half of the continent, with a stronghold in the top end of the Northern Territory.
description: A strangler fig with pale grey bark and growing to approximately 25m.
cultivation: Due to its growth habit, best planted in areas that are not at risk of being damaged by the root system. A beautiful park tree, planted in full or part sun.

range: Grows in coastal rainforests from north east New South Wales through to tropical north Queensland.
description: A strangler fig with aerial roots and growing to approximately 35m. Often germinates after deposition by birds on other trees.
cultivation: This species is often seen growing over other trees, but can grow as a free standing specimen also. Grows in full or part sun on a range of soils, but prefers some moisture and enrichment. Too large or most urban gardens but perfect for rainforest blocks or parks. Excellent shade giving tree.

range: Found in coastal regions of the northern half of the continent.
description: Attractive grass like tufted sedge with rusty brown flower spikes.
cultivation: A wetland species that grows in very damp or wet spots. Ideal for the edges of ponds or boggy spots.

range: Range extends through much of eastern Queensland, typically in rainforest areas.
description: Medium sized rainforest tree to 30m with a dense crown of foliage, clusters of small white flowers and very attractive seed pods.
cultivation: A very hardy tree suiting a range of conditions, that is ideal as a shade tree. Can be grown as a street tree, wind break or simply used as a feature specimen.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
cultivation: Tree to 40 m high with attractive leaf arrangement, clusters of small white flowers followed by ornamental seed pods.

range: Found in coastal regions of Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Evergreen, fast growing tree to 10m with a dense, rounded or spreading crown of attractive dark green foliage. Large sprays of honey-scented small white flowers and interesting woody seed pods
cultivation: Plant in full sun in well drained soils, tending towards rainforest conditions.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: Evergreen, fast growing tree to 10m with a dense, rounded or spreading crown of attractive dark green foliage. Large sprays of honey-scented small white flowers and interesting woody seed pods
cultivation: Plant in full sun in well drained soils, tending towards rainforest conditions.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: Medium tree to 25m with a bushy crown. Cream flowers with a musty perfume.
cultivation: Slow growing, well drained soil, sun or semi shade. Frost hardy.

range: Large range through the eastern coastline of the continent an all of Tasmania.
description: Forms large clumps 1.5 to 2 metres in diameter with flowering stems reaching 3 metres. Flowers occur in spring and summer at the ends of the stems in long spikes and are black in colour. The flowers are followed by shiny, red-brown seeds.
cultivation: Hardy in most soils and climates but grows best if given plenty of water.

range: Natural range through much of eastern Australia to southern New South Wales.
description: Makes a good shade tree that can handle coastal conditions.
cultivation: Hardy in most sunny well drained situations but benefits from watering in early stages.

range: Natural range from central New South Wales coast just extending into south east Queensland.
description: Densely foliaged rainforest tree to 15m with bright red new flushes.
cultivation: Full or part sun in a sheltered moist well drained situation.

range: Common plant across rainforests and sclerophyll forests of Queensland, New South Wales and Northern Territory. Also found in Western Australia.
description: Large shrub or tree with glossy green leaves  and yellow flowers that develop into white-pink fruits.
cultivation: A hardy plant that grows well in many gardens.

range: In rainforest, often in or adjoining palm forest or swamp sclerophyll forest, on the coast from northern New South Wales to the top end in Northern Territory.
description: Attractive rainforest tree with glossy leaves, cheese shaped fruits and a graceful habit.
cultivation: Full or part sun in a sheltered moist well drained situation.

range: Eastern Australia from north Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: A fast growing, deciduous, small to medium tree with masses of white and purple flowers that cover the tree every three to four years.
cultivation: Ideal for somewhat larger gardens, plant in part shade in well drained soil.

range: Eastern Australia from north Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: Small golden yellow pea flower on a small delicate shrub with fine stems only to 30cm high.
cultivation: Grows on sandy, rocky soils in full or part sun.

range: Found along the coast of southern Queensland into New South Wales.
description: An erect, branched shrub growing up to 1.5m in height and about 1m wide. Flowers are bright yellow.
cultivation: Grows on sandy, rocky soils in full or part sun.

range: Large range in the south east of the continent.
description: Very adaptable ground covering plant that features interesting divided foliage and massed, showy golden yellow flowers throughout the warmer months.
cultivation: It tolerates drought conditions and perfect for many urban garden positions.

range: Common across Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Prostrate and sometimes upright herb with round, toothed 'pie-crust'-like leaves. Bright yellow flowers
cultivation: Makes good ground cover in cultivation. Grows in a range of soils and conditions, except very moist areas.

range: Coastal regions from central Queensland south into South Australia, then an isolated population in far south west Australia.
description: Small to medium, spreading shrub of fairly open habit with golden yellow and red flowers. It may reach 3m high is some situations but is usually smaller in open positions.
cultivation: Quite hardy and suited to a range of soil types, with good drainage. Grows in full sun but is more attractive in dappled shade. Keep moist.

range: Most of coastal Queensland south to central New South Wales.
description: Small bushy tree to 10m with orange bark that has green blotches and white flowers.
cultivation: Tolerates coastal conditions and grows well in part shade with well drained soil.

range: Found along the central Queensland coast. Local.
description: A tall slender, spreading shrub to 7m in height. Flowers are bright-red or pale pink to white.
cultivation: Grows in a range of soils with at least some drainage and full sun. Will tolerate only light frost.

range: Grows in southern sub-tropical and coastal regions of Queensland and the very north-eastern tip of New South Wales.
description: Tree or shrub between 3 and 30m in height with elongated spikes of cream flowers.
cultivation: Grows in a variety of soils in either full or part sun.

range: Grows in southern Queensland and northern New South Wales in coastal forests and mountains.
description: Medium to large tree reaching 40m but usually much less, especially as an ornamental. Interesting leaves and golden flower heads. Deciduous.
cultivation: Suited to gardens with space to accommodate a medium sized tree.

range: Stronghold of range in coastal New South Wales, extending up Queensland coast at lower density.
description: Small rainforest tree to 6m bushy canopy of dark green foliage with clusters of flowers that develop into bird attracting fruits.
cultivation: Plant in full sun. A useful shelter tree for other plants, adapting to most soils and conditions.

range: Local in northern New South Wales and south-east Queensland.
description: A sparse shrub that can reach up to 5m in height, but is usually a great deal smaller. Dainty white flowers amongst needle like leaves.
cultivation: A hardy plant that tolerates coastal zones well. Plant in full sun.

range: Very large distribution through most of Australia's interior except New South Wales and Victoria.
description: Shrub or small tree to 10 m high with erect or drooping foliage
cultivation: It is best suited to inland regions with a dry sunny climate. Quite slow growing.

range: Scattered populations through eastern to inland parts of Queensland.
