description: An upright shrub to 4m with dense clusters of fragrant cream (or sometimes pink) flowers in winter and spring.
cultivation: Plant full sun or partial shade, well drained sites.

range: Common in Victoria and eastern half of New South Wales and to lesser extent in eastern Queensland. Another hotspot around south eastern South Australia.
description: Climbing shrub or vine reaching 2m. Stunning purple flowers attract bees.
cultivation: Grows in a wide variety of habitats, tolerating a range of soils. Best flowering will occur in sunnier positions.

range: Most of coastal Queensland south to central New South Wales.
description: Small to medium tree to 15m with glossy green leaves and orange fruits.
cultivation: Ideal shade tree in urban gardens, plant in full sun on well drained soils.

range: Found from northern New South Wales into tropical Queensland.
description: Rather a small tree to 12m with insignificant flowers but the fruit are very attractive.
cultivation: A popular street tree, this species will grow in a variety of soils and positions.

range: Stronghold of range in coastal New South Wales, extending up Queensland coast and south to Victoria at lower density.
description: A beautiful, bushy prostrate shrub growing to only 30cm tall but up to 1 m across. Small grey green oval leaves and masses of bright yellow flowers from Spring to Summer. Moderate frost tolerance.
cultivation: Ideal as a ground cover herby shrub. Plant in full sun in drained soils.

range: Stronghold of range in coastal New South Wales, extending into south east Queensland and north east Victoria.
description: Non-vigorous climbing or trailing plant, growing to 1 to 2 metres in length with yellow flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full or part shade in reasonably well drained soils.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: Robust climbing plant with  leaves that are glossy and smooth. Bright yellow flowers attract insects.
cultivation: Will tolerate a wide range of climates, including exposure to salt-laden winds. Makes an excellent screening plant on walls or fences, or growing as a scrambler among more established plants. However, it can easily smother smaller plants.

range: Common in the northern New South Wales and southern Queensland coastal forests.
description: A prostrate or sprawling shrub growing up to 30cm tall with bright yellow flowers.
cultivation: Grows in full sun and requires minimal watering. Tolerates salt air.

range: Common through eastern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Shrub or sometimes small tree with prickly stems/branches. Large flowers in a range of colours that are short-lived.
cultivation: Tolerant of a range of conditions, including light frost.

range: Found throughout the eastern seaboard of New South Wales and Queensland in suitable habitat.
description: Tall shrub to 6m in height. Large pink flowers.
cultivation: An attractive and hardy species in a range of soils and climates.

range: Coastal range in the north east of the continent from the top end in the Northern Territory to central New South Wales.
description: An evergreen, fast growing large shrub or small tree to 8m with a wide spreading crown of attractive dark green, rounded to heart-shaped foliage and bright yellow flowers with crimson centres.
cultivation: An ideal shade tree, screen or windbreak for coastal gardens tolerating full exposure to sun, salt water and strong, salt laden winds. Also tolerates bore water and poor draining soils.

range: Native to subtropical rainforest in New South Wales and Queensland
description: Slender ornamental shrub to 10m often multi stemmed with flushes of red new growth.
cultivation: Well drained site in sun or light shade.

range: Common through eastern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: An attractive small tree with decorative leaves and bird attracting fruit.
cultivation: Requires a moist soil in either full sun or part shade. It is a useful revegetation plant which grows rapidly on disturbed sites as a pioneer plant.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: Upright shrub growing to 3m. Interesting green foliage with rusty coloured hairs giving a golden look to stems. Clusters of stunning purple flowers in Spring.
cultivation: Plant in well drained soil with part shade. Can be short lived (5-7 years) but successionally planting of mixed ages will ensure a steady stream of healthy plants. Readily propagated from seeds.

range: Naturally occurs from far north Queensland to north east New South Wales. Predominantly east of the Dividing Range.
description: A slightly downy climber growing to 6m scrambling over rocks and tree trunks. Flowers have waxy white petals with a red blotch near centre.
cultivation: Grows in shade or semi-shade with a climbing habit.

range: Native to eastern sub-tropical Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Tall shrub or small tree to 20m, but usually much less. Flowers are silky inside, fragrant and pale yellow or cream.
cultivation: Native frangipani likes a position in full sun to dappled shade, with protection from strong winds. Alkaline soils best.

range: Large range though much of Australia.
description: Clumping grass with soil stabilising properties and ideal habitat for waterbirds and ground nesting birds.
cultivation: Great planted along side ponds and dams or mass plant for impact. Tolerant of a range of conditions including full sun, drought, salty air and poor soils.

range: Widespread in open forest and woodlands in southern Australia from the south-east of Western Australia to north-east Queensland.
description: A shrub to 2m with attractive pink or purple flowers.
cultivation: A hardy plant in a range of well drained soils but performs best in part shade with some provisional watering and moderate pruning of newer growth after flowering.

range: Native to coastal Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Climbing vine or ground cover with large green leaves and purple flowers that open each morning and close at night.
cultivation: Perfect on sandy soils in full sun. The creeper provides an important stabilising function on fore dunes and helps to prevent further erosion from prevailing winds.

range: Native to south east Queensland and eastern New South Wales.
description: Shrub or small tree up to 4 m high with sun yellow flowers in spring and summer.
cultivation: Adaptable species for a range of well drained soils in full sun or partial shade.

range: Found from Coffs Harbour in New South Wales to tropical Queensland.
description: Small tree to 10m. It is named after the foamy saponin that leaks from the bark after heavy rainstorms. Insignificant flowers followed by interesting fruit.
cultivation: Plant in full sun. A hardy tree that will tolerate light frost.

range: Large range through south eastern Australia.
description: Perennial rush to 1.2m with a clumping habit and red-golden seed heads.
cultivation: Plant in full sun in boggy or damp soils. Can tolerate dry periods but needs inundation periodically.

range: Relatively well distributed in south-east Queensland and northern New South Wales.
description: Medium-sized cycad with a stout trunk to 7m. Leaves reach 2-3m.
cultivation: If drainage is good, this species can withstand a range of conditions. Enjoys dappled shade and can tolerate drought.

range: North eastern New South Wales and south east Queensland in sandy, swampy coastal heath.
description: Erect shrub to about 2m high  with small white flowers and aromatic properties that are reminiscent of citronella.
cultivation: A very hardy species that will tolerate poor drainage. It is suited to sun or partial shade and will tolerate at least moderate frost and responds well to pruning

range: Native to eastern Australia. Common.
description: Densely-vegetated  shrub with leaves often aromatic. Small white flowers. There are several cultivars of this species with pink flowers.
cultivation: It tends to be long-lived in cultivation, but requires sunny positions. Grows on sandy soils in open forests and along rivers.

range: North eastern New South Wales and south east Queensland in sandy, swampy coastal heath.
description: Small shrub to 1m with a weeping habit, flaking bark and small whit flowers in winter to spring.
cultivation: Hardy to moderate frost, prefers moist sandy soils & sun or part shade.

range: Rainforests of eastern Queensland into northern New South Wales.
description: Medium tree to 12m with large green leaves and fragrant cream flowers.
cultivation: Suited to areas adjacent to native rainforest (well drained soils and adequate rainfall) to maximise chances of pollination and provide a valuable resource to rainforest birds.

range: Widespread in coastal rainforests of Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Palm tree to 30m high with a single stem reaching 50cm in diameter. Young plants are much smaller creating broad shady structures on the forest floor. Large fan-like leaves.
cultivation: Grows in moist soils in either full sun or part shade.

range: Coastal species from north Queensland to south Queensland.
description: Decorative palm to 18m tall with clumped crowns of foliage.
cultivation: Grows in moist soils in either full sun or part shade.

range: Found in Queensland, New South Wales and Victoria. Common.
description: A clumping, tufted perennial herb with elongated erect stems. Leaves linear reaching 70cm long and 3cm wide with tiny teeth along margins. Flowers often scented. Fruit a green berry.
cultivation: Grows in a range of soil types and enjoys full sun or part shade.

range: Found in eastern New South Wales and Queensland.
description: A clumping, tufted perennial herb with elongated erect stems. Leaves linear reaching over a metre long. Flowers often scented. Fruit a green berry.
cultivation: A useful plant for revegetation and erosion control. Plant in a range of soil conditions, especially along water courses in part shade.

range: Large range through eastern Australia.
description: A clumping, tufted perennial herb with elongated erect stems. Leaves linear reaching over a metre long. Flowers often scented. Fruit a green berry.
cultivation: Tolerant and hardy to a range of conditions, from damp to dry soils and full sun to part shade. A useful plant for revegetation and erosion control.

range: Found across forested landscapes in southern coastal Queensland and northern New South Wales.
description: This tree can grow very large, both in height and girth. Rich red-brown bark and leaves in a distinctive whorled arrangement.
cultivation: Grows in both drier and wetter areas. Ultimate size will depend on conditions it grows in, getting larger in wetter areas.

range: Found in swampy areas from Cape York to central New South Wales.
description: Medium tree to 15m in cultivation. Clusters of white flowers in spring and summer.
cultivation: Grows in both drier and wetter areas. Plant in full sun as a valuable habitat tree for birds and source of nectar for bees and butterflies.

range: Northern distribution from north east New South Wales through south east Queensland to north Western Australia.
description: Creeping or climbing fern, with fronds reaching 20cm long.
cultivation: Enjoys a shady moist position.

range: Small range in the rainforests of south east Queensland.
description: Small to medium sized tree to about 15 metres with a bushy habit, glossy leaves and white flowers that develop into the characteristic macadamia nut.
cultivation: Hardy in a range of climates and soils but prefers good drainage and humus-rich soils.

range: Rare, found in a coastal belt from the Tweed River north to the Gold Coast hinterland and Mount Wongawallan.
description: A small-medium tree growing to 15m in height with red-coloured new growth.
cultivation: Will thrive in richer soils that don’t become waterlogged.

range: Found throughout coastal Queensland as well as the Northern Territory. Common.
description: A shrub or small tree growing to 6m. Attractive heart-shaped leaves give cool shade and small pale green flowers are visited by small birds.
cultivation: Thrives in a mix of conditions, including many soil types. Hardy to salt air.

range: Found in coastal areas through much of Queensland into north eastern New South Wales.
description: A compact admirable garden tree to 15 m with bright yellow fruits.
cultivation: A fast growing tree if given sufficient water and nutrients, both male and female forms need to be grown if fruit and seed are required.

range: Common along the coastal fringes of Queensland and New South Wales.
description: A bush or small-medium tree growing to 25m with yellow inconspicuous flowers.
cultivation: Grows naturally in rainforest edges. Very hardy tree to 10m. Suitable tree for reforestation purposes, especially in difficult positions.

range: Rainforests of south eastern Queensland into north eastern New South Wales.
description: A small rainforest shrubby tree to 6m with white flowers and glossy green leaves.
cultivation: Must have good drainage and prefers a sheltered site in light shade, tolerates light frost.

range: Range extends over much of northern Australia in patchy populations.
description: Variable shrub to 10m, but most often 6m. Dense foliage and small white flowers in spring and summer.
cultivation: Prefers moist but well-drained soil in full sun.

range: Small range in south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Shrubby tree to fine green foliage and small white flowers in spring and summer.
cultivation: Prefers moist but well-drained soil in full sun.

range: A coastal species found along the coast of New South Wales and Queensland in suitable habitat.
description: A shrub or small, rounded tree growing to a height of 10m, but usually much less. Masses of white flower spikes make it look like it's covered in snow.
cultivation: Grows best on moist ground in full sun. Good for boggy spots.

range: A coastal species found along the coast of central New South Wales and south east Queensland in suitable habitat.
cultivation: Performs well in full sun and responds well to light fertiliser applications and annual pruning. Tolerant of poorly drained soils.

range: Widespread and common in southern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Medium paperbark tree with erect green fragrant leaves and cream flower spikes.
cultivation: Grows in full sun and able to withstand very moist soils as it naturally occurs in swamps.

range: Natural range in south east Queensland and eastern New South Wales.
description: A small tree to 8m with pendulous foliage and white, pink or red flower spikes.
cultivation: Tolerates a range of soil types, enjoys fairly sunny positions and requires adequate water in the early stages. Drought tolerant once established.

range: Widespread and common in coastal southern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: A small shrubby tree to 10m with evergreen foliage and white or pink spikes.
cultivation: Grows in full sun and able to withstand very moist soils as it naturally occurs in coastal sandy swamps.

range: Common in very southern borderlands of Queensland and across New South Wales.
description: Attractive straggly shrub to 2m high. Flowers purple or pink in heads at the end of branches.
cultivation: Will grow in a range of conditions, but will flower best in sunny positions with adequate water. Also responds well to moderate pruning after flowering.

range: Main stronghold through eastern Queensland, stretching inland beyond the Dividing Range.
description: A small to medium tree that can be trained to be more shrub like. Weeping branches and bright red flower spikes.
cultivation: Tolerates a range of soil types, enjoys fairly sunny positions and requires adequate water in the early stages. Drought tolerant once established.

range: Widespread distribution across the north of the continent. Southernmost limit to southeast Queensland.
description: Small tree to 10m with cream or red flower spikes.
cultivation: Adaptable to a wide range of soils and conditions but does particularly well on heavy clays which are waterlogged in the wet.

range: Native to coastal New South Wales, Queensland, Northern Territory and Western Australia. Common.
description: A leafy shrub to 2m in height with purple flowers.
cultivation: Hardy to a wide range of soils and situations, but sensitive to dry conditions and frost. An attractive hardy shrub suitable for tropical to warm temperate regions.

range: Dry and coastal rainforests extending from tropical areas of Western Australia, the Northern Territory and Queensland to the south coast of New South Wales.
description: A small to medium deciduous tree with rich green foliage and mauve flowers followed by yellow fruits that are attractive to birds.
cultivation: Hardy to a wide range of soils and situations. Plant in full or part sun.

range: Patchy coastal distribution from north east New South Wales to north west Australia.
description: A fast growing rainforest tree to 10m with masses of pink flowers along the branches in summer, attracting many species of birds and butterflies.
cultivation: Plant in an open sunny position in well drained soil.

range: Native to south eastern regions from south east Queensland to Tasmania.
description: Unusual fern with large leaves in the shape of kangaroo paws. Grows to approximately 30cm in height.
cultivation: Grow in filtered light shady positions with adequate moisture supply.

range: Large range through eastern and northern Australia.
description: Herbaceous lily-like plant that grows to 60cm with purple flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full to part sun in well drained soil.

range: Patchy distribution across the whole continent with the stronghold of population in the coastal areas of New South Wales.
description: Shrubby tree to 8m that occurs in coastal regions. Attractive foliage and flowers.
cultivation: It prefers well drained soil in full sun and can tolerate salt spray.

range: Widely distributed in coastal areas from far north Queensland to south coast of New South Wales.
description: Dark green glossy foliage and many branches help this plant form a dense cover of foliage covering 1.5m across. It bears tiny white flowers in the warmer months.
cultivation: Quite hardy and performs at its best when mass planted. Especially suited to coastline areas.

range: Widespread in eastern Queensland and New South Wales.
description: A bushy tree to 8m with showy pinkish-purple new growth and small creamy white bell shaped flowers.
cultivation: Prefers a cool partially shaded site with adequate moisture.

range: Common along the New South Wales and Queensland rainforest coasts.
description: A small tree or shrub to 12m high. Unusual yellow flowers from stems followed by dark purple fruits.
cultivation: Grows in full or part sun. A rainforest plant that also tolerates drier conditions once established.

range: Extremely rare, found only in the Ipswich area in three gully locations.
description: A small, multi-stemmed shrub with evergreen leaves growing to 1-2m in height. It produces small yellowish-cream flowers followed by small purple-coloured fruit.
cultivation: Low fertility soils and sandstone parent rock material are what this species grows in naturally. Full sun is ideal.

range: Very rare, restricted to only eight sites in south-east Queensland from the Mt Crosby area south-west to Moogerah Peaks National Park.
description: A shrub growing up to 4m in height, but usually less. Flowers grow in groups of up to 20 with fruit that is spherical-ovoid resembling a hard, woody nut with thin, dark blue skin.
cultivation: Grows in rocky soils that are shallow and well drained.

range: Native to rainforest edges and riparian areas from far north Queensland to central New South Wales.
description: Bushy tree to 15m often with sparse canopy.
cultivation: Fast  pioneer for sunny protected site. Well drained soil essential.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: Shrub growing to 1 or 2m in height with many branching stems. Typical white and yellow daisy flowers.
cultivation: Plant in well drained soil with some dappled shade.

range: Stronghold of distribution in eastern New South Wales with clusters of occurrence in southern and northern Queensland.
description: Stunning juvenile foliage and very showy flowers make this plant highly ornamental.
cultivation: Plant in part shade and in a well drained position.

range: Distributed through eastern New South Wales and south east Queensland.
description: Small shrub to 1.5m with aromatic leaves and pretty pink flowers.
cultivation: Trim back after each flower flush to trigger a new burst of blooms.

range: Common across the Queensland and New South Wales coastline.
description: A branched shrub or tree to 12m tall with tubular, thick, corky prop roots that descend from the lower stem in snake-like protrusions. Long strap like leaves and large white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in  well drained soils in a sunny location. Salt air tolerant.

range: Found in south-east Queensland and north-eastern New South Wales only.
description: A tall (or sometimes creeping) woody climber that has vigorous growth. Pale pink flowers with a magenta tubular throat.
cultivation: A very hardy species suited to many soil types. Enjoys sunny positions and is moderately tolerant to frost once established. A vigorous climber, so plant accordingly.

range: Widespread in eastern Australia.
description: Scrambling vine with twisted stems and pink-whitish flowers with purple blotches and stripes.
cultivation: Prefers an open, sunny position and a mild climate. It will tolerate light shade and frosts.

range: Very small range with two hotspots in far south east and north east Queensland.
description: Woody climber with yellow and purple flowers. Important food source for the Richmond Birdwing Butterfly.
cultivation: Select plants that are already approximately now 2 years old. Plant in part shade or full sun, but ensure moisture is adequate in full sun positions in well drained soil with organic matter.

range: Large range through eastern Australia from Cape York to southern New South Wales.
description: A delicate tendril climbing vine with attractive white and pink flowers.
cultivation: Adaptable to a range of conditions, but performs best in richer soils with adequate drainage and part to full sun.

range: Stronghold in eastern New South Wales, but extending into south east Queensland with an additional cluster around north Queensland.
description: A delicate tendril climbing vine with attractive lemon yellow and white flowers.
cultivation: Adaptable to a range of conditions, but performs best in richer soils with adequate drainage and part to full sun.

range: Found throughout the eastern coastal lowlands of Australia down to Victoria. Common.
description: Tufted herb to about 60cm in height with long strap-like leaves that grow at the base of the plant. Beautiful purple flowers.
cultivation: Grows in sandy soils in part shade.

range: Naturally occurs along eastern parts of Queensland.
description: Showy white flowered bushy shrub to 5m. Very decorative garden plant that is currently under appreciated as a cultivation species.
cultivation: Prefers a warm sheltered semi-shaded moist site. Extra water needed in dry times.

range: Stronghold in eastern New South Wales, but extending into south east Queensland with an additional cluster around north Queensland.
description: A small hardy fern with broad leaves compared to many other fern species.
cultivation: As with most ferns, plant in a shady position with adequate moisture available.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales with another hotspot in central New South Wales.
description: Ornamental small bushy tree to 12m with very showy white scented flowers.
cultivation: Hardy in most soils & sites. Moderately fast & frost tolerant. Full sun.

range: Common along the northern New South Wales and south eastern Queensland coasts.
description: Erect shrub to 6m with yellow flowers and attractive foliage.
cultivation: Plant in full sun in well drained soils.

range: Large range through north eastern Australia.
description: Bushy small tree to 4m tall with attractive foliage and orange fruits.
cultivation: Ideal in coastal settings. Plant in full or part sun in well drained soils.

range: Clustered populations throughout south east Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Shrub to 1m with fine needle like foliage and cream coloured flowers.
cultivation: Naturally occurs on sandy swampy heaths, so plant in full sun in well drained soils that receive adequate moisture.

range: Small range in south east Queensland.
description: Shrub to 1m with fine needle like foliage and cream coloured flowers.
cultivation: Naturally occurs on sandy swampy heaths, so plant in full sun in well drained soils that receive adequate moisture.

range: Very rare, now confined mostly to the sand islands of Queensland and north-eastern New South Wales. A few localities on the mainland.
description: A spectacular, large ground orchid growing to 2m in height. Flowers are roughly star-shaped and are cream on the outside and deep reddish-brown on the inner surface
cultivation: Plant in a relatively shady damp position that mimics their natural swamp loving habit.

range: Rare orchid in swamps of south east Queensland.
description: A spectacular, large ground orchid growing to 2m in height. Flowers are roughly star-shaped and are yellow and cream.
cultivation: Plant in a relatively shady damp position that mimics their natural swamp loving habit.

range: Found throughout heath areas of south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: A small to medium shrub to about 2m high by 1.5m wide with dainty white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full sun in well drained soils. Prune after flowering.

range: Range extends through coastal areas of eastern and northern parts of the continent.
description: Swampy or aquatic species with strappy leaves to 60cm and yellow flowers.
cultivation: Ideal on creek banks and edges of ponds. Plant in full or part sun.

range: Range extends through south eastern parts of the continent.
description: Swampy species with large grass-like form to 6m in height.
cultivation: Ideal on creek banks and edges of ponds. Plant in full or part sun.

range: Range extends through south eastern parts of the continent.
description: Small erect shrub to 1m with small white flowers in globular clusters.
cultivation: Versatile species making an attractive ground cover or low shrub. Grows best in soil with some drainage.

range: Found throughout eastern Australian states from Queensland to Tasmania.
description: A tall, broad shrub or small tree to 15m high. Fragrant white flowers followed by bright orange fruits.
cultivation: Naturally grows in rainforest or wet eucalypt conditions, but adaptable.

range: Coastal range through all of Queensland into north east New South Wales.
description: Bushy tree to 12m, understory of the rainforest is the natural habitat.
cultivation: Naturally grows in rainforest or wet eucalypt conditions in sites with good drainage.

range: Grows on a variety of trees in rainforests through eastern Australia.
description: An epiphytic fern (growing on trees).
cultivation: Plants require a shady anchor point on a tree to grow in, and need to be kept moist.

range: Grows on a variety of trees in rainforests through eastern Australia.
description: An epiphytic fern (growing on trees).
cultivation: Bought in small pots where the nest frond will have to mature before producing fertile fronds. Tend to be heavy once established. It is popular to grow them mounted onto hardwood boards and hung up on a trellis or planted in a hanging basket suspended from a secure point on the ceiling. In warmer areas they can be attached directly to the trunk of a tree in the garden.

range: Small range in Ipswich and Ormeau areas.
description: Hairy herb to 60cm with showy purple flower spikes throughout the year.
cultivation: Plant in part shade in well drained soil.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: Hairy herb to 40cm with showy purple flower spikes throughout the year.
cultivation: Plant in part shade in well drained soil.

range: Large range through eastern Australia from north Queensland to eastern Victoria.
description: Hairy herb to 60cm with variegated foliage and showy purple flower spikes throughout the year.
cultivation: Plant in part shade in well drained soil.

range: Naturally occurs in the northern half of Queensland with a small population extending into south eastern parts.
description: A medium sized tree to approximately 15m with glossy leaves and dark red fruits.
cultivation: Usually a species of rainforest and wet eucalypt areas, it is best suited to moist enriched soils with good drainage.

range: Range extends through south eastern parts of the continent.
description: An ornamental clumping grass to 1m.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in most soil types. Ideal is planted in rows to form edges.

range: Patchy range from far north Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: A attractive medium sized tree with fleshy cones that attract birds. Male and female plants grow independently, thus both are needed for fruit yield.
cultivation: Best suited to soils that are rich in organic matter and have adequate drainage.

range: Isolated populations in south east Queensland, north east New South Wales and south east New South Wales.
description: Medium shrub to 2m with attractive green foliage and fruits on female plants, requiring pollination from a male plant nearby.
cultivation: Best suited to soils that are rich in organic matter and have adequate drainage.

range: Naturally occurs in coastal areas from near Townsville to far north east New South Wales.
description: A rainforest tree to 15m with dense green foliage, small cream flowers followed by small black fruits.
cultivation: Adapted for sites tending to rainforest conditions. Well drained soil and part sun.

range: Stronghold of population in central to south east Queensland.
description: Vivid green foliage in characteristic lily shape. Very attractive white flowers in a cluster at the end of a tall stalk.
cultivation: Best suited for well composted soil in sheltered areas of the garden with little sun.

range: South east Queensland through eastern New South Wales.
description: A medium sized shrub with masses of purple flowers and highly aromatic leaves.
cultivation: Ideal for well drained soils that can be a little moist. Part sun is best, especially in warmer months. Prune each year to retain bushy growth.

range: Range extends through eastern parts of the continent.
description: Shrub to about 3m with hairy leaves and small white flowers.
cultivation: A hardy shrub which does well in coastal districts in full sun or part shade. Suited to enriched soils with good drainage.

range: Range extends through eastern regions of Queensland and north east New South Wales. Small population near Darwin.
description: A medium to large shrub to 8m with glossy green leaves, bunches of small white flowers followed by black fruits.
cultivation: Requires well drained soils and prefers a position sheltered from full sun. Not frost tolerant in early stages.

range: Naturally occurs in rainforest margins near streams in south east Australia.
description: Attractive fern up to 2m tall, but usually less.
cultivation: Plant in shady positions that are damp and receive regualr water.

range: Inland distribution from north Queensland to western Victoria.
description: Relatively short-lived perennial herb with very pretty mauve flower spikes.
cultivation: Plant in hot sunny positions. Ideal for rockeries and edges of retaining walls.

range: Large range across inland areas of Australia from central west to east. Also occurs in a hotspot in western Victoria.
description: Relatively short-lived perennial herb with very pretty cream flower heads.
cultivation: Plant in hot sunny positions. Ideal for rockeries and edges of retaining walls.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland and clusters along New South Wales coast.
description: Erect shrub 1m - 2m with small leaves and yellow pea flowers with a red centre.
cultivation: Easy to grow in partial shade on poor or clayey soils.

range: Extends from south east Queensland south along the New South Wales coast.
description: Erect or sometimes prostrate shrub covered in curly pale hairs. Branches often have drooping habit. Flowers are bright orange with a red blotch.
cultivation: A common plant in cultivation which is easy to grow in partial shade on poor soils.

range: Found throughout inland south eastern Australia.
cultivation: In the wild they grow in rather swampy places, so keep moist but well drained. Very frost tolerant, and can take dry periods and coastal sites. Grows from an underground rhizome, so if the plant dies off, it can resprout.

range: Grows in coastal or eastern rainforests from south east Queensland to south New South Wales.
description: Shrub or small tree to 12m with glossy green leaves and very pretty white flowers.
cultivation: A hardy plant but performs best wityh adequate water supply. Responds well to pruning to retain dense growth.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland and north eastern New South Wales.
description: A small tree to 15m with attractive foliage, red flowers and brown berries.
cultivation: Drought and frost hardy, plant in full or part sun in reasonably well drained soils.

range: Grows in coastal heaths from central Queensland to Victoria and Tasmania.
description: Bushy shrub to 2m with masses of beautiful white flowers.
cultivation: Grows in a range of soils, but needs full sun. Can be planted in hedges using mass plantings.

range: Extends from far north Queensland along the coastal zone south to eastern Victoria.
description: Tall scrambling climber, sometimes forming bushes.
cultivation: Grow in a damp area that gets at least partial sun.

range: Small population in south east Queensland, but occupies the whole east coast of New South Wales and eastern Victoria.
description: Medium height dense shrub. White flowers attract bees and red fruits attract birds.
cultivation: Grow in a damp area that gets at least partial sun.

range: Common through eucalypt and rainforest margins in south east Queensland and central New South Wales.
description: A bushy shrub to 2m with aromatic leaves and small white flowers followed by a small white fruit.
cultivation: Performs well in full or part sun in a range of soils.

range: Large range of isolated hot spots from south east Australia to the inland parts of the Northern Territory.
description: Low shrub to 60cm with purple and yellow fan shaped flowers.
cultivation: Can be grown in a range of conditions and makes a very attractive ground cover. Not frost tolerant and benefits from some watering in extended dry times.

range: Grows in coastal dunes from central Queensland to South Australia.
description: Small shrub to 40cm with fleshy green leaves and mauve fan shaped flowers.
cultivation: Perfect for coastal gardens as this plant is naturally suited to sandy soils. Tolerant of a range of soils and grows in full or part sun.

range: Grows throughout the south east of Australia in moist sometimes swampy habitats. Also a river or creek line species.
description: Tall sedge to 1 or 2m. Upright green/blue reed like plant with rusty brown coloured flowers and seeds.
cultivation: Plant in full sun to part shade with adequate water available.

range: Very large range covering most of inland Australia, with occurrences to coastal districts in the east and west of Australia.
description: Medium shrub to 2m with leaves covered in silvery hairs and bright yellow flowers.
cultivation: Plant in well drained sandy soils and stony soils in full sun. Suited to more arid areas, but benefits from incidental waterings.

range: Coastal range through the northern half of the continent.
description: Creeping ground cover succulent herb with small purple flowers
cultivation: Grows in sandy or muddy soils in coastal areas. Enjoys full sun but can tolerate some shade.

synonyms: Blush Alder, Blush Carrabeen, Blush Barrobean, Cudgerie
range: Two eastern centres of distribution, one in far north Queensland and then a larger range in south east Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: A medium sized rainforest tree to 10m with showy white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in well drained soil in a sheltered position in either sun or part shade.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland north eastern New South Wales.
description: A medium sized rainforest tree to 15m with showy white flowers.
cultivation: Plant in well drained soil in a sheltered position in either sun or part shade.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland and far north eastern New South Wales.
description: Attractive weeping shrub with soft greyish foliage and golden yellow flowers.
cultivation: Plant in full or part sun in well drained soil but in an area that receives adequate moisture.

range: Coastal range through the south east of the continent and Tasmania.
description: Perennial herb to 50cm with small fleshy leaves and small white flowers.
cultivation: Naturally grows in heath and eucalypt forest. Grows well in sandy soils in coastal areas.

range: Scattered eastern distribution from far north Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: Medium to large tree to 20m in cultivation with attractive white flowers.
cultivation: Grow in full or part sun in well drained nutrient enriched soil.

range: Largely restricted to Queensland in three strongholds, one being in south east Queensland and north east New South Wales.
description: Medium to large tree to 20m in cultivation with wheel shaped stunning red flowers.
cultivation: Grow in full or part sun in well drained nutrient enriched soil.

range: Extends from north west Australia along coastal areas to far north east New South Wales.
description: A fast growing rainforest tree to 8m in cultivation. Orange seed pods ripen to expose red interior of pod containing dark nuts.
cultivation: Grows in areas that tend towards rainforest conditions. Needs free draining soil and warm conditions. Not frost tolerant.

range: Found throughout south east of Australia, including Tasmania.
description: A small herb with grass like leaves and flower spikes that have very pretty pink-mauve flowers.
cultivation: Appreciates well drained soils in a sunny or lightly shaded situation.

range: Stronghold in eastern New South Wales extending into the greater south east Queensland region.
description: Long-lived shrubby perennial to with very pretty pink-mauve pea flowers.
cultivation: They thrive in any soil, are useful for a quick cover in a difficult situation and excellent as single specimens.

range: Found as an emergent tree species from southern New South Wales north to Queensland.
description: A tall, slender tree with fibrous and stringy persistent bark, which is dark reddish-brown in colour. Flowers are bright white
cultivation: Grows on a range of soils from clay to sandy. Plant in full or part sun.

range: Scattered eastern distribution from far north Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: Small tree to 5m with glossy green leaves, white flowers and orange fruits that split to expose orange seeds.
cultivation: Fairly fast growng in well-drained soil, prefers a protected site in light shade.

range: Common in suitable forests from Queensland to Victoria.
description: A small tree or shrub with glossy green leaves, white fluffy flowers and blush pink fruits.
cultivation: Grows in a range of conditions but their natural habitat tends to be rainforest.

synonyms: Brush Berry, Creek Satinash, Scrub Cherry
range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland eastern New South Wales.
description: Versatile shrubby tree 15m with fluffy white flowers and red fruits.
cultivation: Prefers rich, well drained soils but will survive in poorer soils as well. Plant in full or part sun.

range: Stronghold in north eastern New South Wales and south eastern Queensland with isolated occurrences in north Queensland.
description: An excellent small shade tree to 15m with a dense canopy. Small cream flowers, pear-shaped fleshy red  fruit
cultivation: Prefers rich, well drained soils but will survive in poorer soils as well. Plant in full or part sun.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland and north eastern New South Wales.
description: Attractive tree to 15m with very showy red new growth & bushy growth habit, small white flowers & purple globular berry
cultivation: Tolerant of a range of soils, plant in full or part sun.

range: Relatively small distribution in south east Queensland and north eastern New South Wales.
description: Shrub to 2m with dense glossy green leaves, fluffy white flowers and mauve fruits that attract birds.
cultivation: Tolerant of a range of soils, plant in full or part sun.

range: Restricted to subtropical rainforest in north east New South Wales and south east Queensland.
description: Medium to large tree up to 40m. New leaves are decorative red before turning dark green. Fluffy cream flowers followed by red fruits.
cultivation: Enjoys moist soil types but not drought tolerant. Plant in sun to part shade.

range: Common in subtropical Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Medium-sized tree with bright pink new growth and flaky bark. Flowers are small with tiny white petals and fruit is a fleshy pink or red berry
cultivation: A very hardy species suited to many soil types. Enjoys sunny positions and is moderately tolerant to frost once established.

range: Eastern Australia from north Queensland to southern New South Wales.
description: Ornamental & fast growing, glossy dark green to yellow foliage, leaves smell lemony when crushed, creamy-white flowers in Summer.
cultivation: Hardy tree for temperate to tropical climates in reasonably well drained soils. Once established it will tolerate extended dry conditions but is at its best when assured water is available.

range: Endemic to Fraser Island but cultivated regularly in the region and far north Queensland.
description: A dense vigorous climber with glossy green leaves and beautiful pink tubular flowers.
cultivation: Grow in part or full sun in well drained soils.

range: Open forests and woodlands of eastern New South Wales and southern Queensland.
description: An ideal garden shrub to 60cm with pretty purple flowers.
cultivation: Plant in a well drained position in the garden, preferably with some shelter from the direct summer sun and with assured moisture.

range: Widespread across all of Australia.
description: A tufted grass that grows to 1.5m tall with attractive weeping seed heads.
cultivation: Grows in full sun to part shade on sandy to clay soils and needs little water once established. Source local stock adapted for local conditions.

range: Widespread throughout south eastern Australia.
description: A rather large fern with fronds up to 2m long, and sometimes forms a trunk with several crowns.
cultivation: Grow in a damper area of the garden preferably not in full sun.

range: New South Wales and Queensland rainforest coasts.
description: A deciduous rainforest tree that is now rare due to depletion for timber trade. Grows to 15m.
cultivation: Naturally adapted to rainforest conditions, but adaptable.

range: Predominantly a coastal species of New South Wales, extending into south east Queensland.
description: Medium to tall tree reaching 30m but usually around 10m. Clusters of yellow flowers among attractive green foliage.
cultivation: Tolerates a variety of soil types from well-drained rocky soils to heavy clay loams, provided ample water is available.

range: Practically endemic to Queensland except for several isolated locations in the Northern Territory and north Western Australia.
description: Shrub or small deciduous tree with attractive and fragrant white flowers that develop into equally attractive fruits.
cultivation: Relatively hardy if planted in soils with drainage.

range: Endemic to McPherson Range
description: Prostrate annual herb with thin trailing stems to 80cm and opposite pairs of small, round, serrated leaves. Flowers are numerous, small and mauve in colour.
cultivation: Plant in shady moist spots or under an established tree.

range: Common along coastal seaboard zones of Queensland and New South Wales.
description: Fast-spreading herb that forms often quite dense ground cover. Pretty white and purple flowers.
cultivation: In cultivation, this plant does well in slightly wetter sites with loam soil and shade. Exercise caution planting near other smaller plants, due to spreading nature.

range: Relatively small distribution covering south east Queensland with some extension into New South Wales.
description: Attractive tree to 15m with glossy green foliage and pink fruits
cultivation: Fast growing and quite hardy. Plant in sun or shade in well drained soil.

range: Found in all states except the Northern Territory.
description: A perennial herb with purple flowers on ling stems.
cultivation: Suited for massed display in a well drained soil in either a sunny or semi-shaded position. As the plants are shallow rooted, the soil should be kept moist but not water-logged.

range: Common in suitable habitat from Hunter Valley, New South Wales north into Queensland.
description: A medium tree with leaves that are typically downward pointing giving the tree its ‘weeping’ habit. White fluffy flowers followed by red fruits.
cultivation: Grows well as a screen plant. Best in moist soils.

range: South east Queensland through to most of eastern New South Wales.
description: A trunkless grass tree. Attractive green narrow leaves and tall flower spikes emerging from base.
cultivation: Grows as a large tuft in sandy soils without a trunk. Great for smaller gardens in a sunny position.

range: Found throughout the region in suitable habitat.
description: Woody plant with a solitary crown of upright spreading needle-shaped leaves resembling a grass. The flowering spike (scape) can reach 2m and bears small white highly-reduced flowers.
cultivation: Grows in well drained soil in full or part sun.

range: Very widely distributed with the Northern Territory being the only area it is not found naturally.
description: A small herb with characteristic daisy flowers. Numerous cultivars of different colours available.
cultivation: Will grow happily in a range of conditions. Perennial and annual varieties available, with perennials benefiting from a prune each year.

range: Stronghold populations in the eastern half of New South Wales with isolated populations into Queensland.
description: A shrub that will grow to less than 1m. Aromatic leaves and attractive pink flowers.
cultivation: Low maintenance and tolerant of a range of conditions, except full sun.
